In France, voting has traditionally been a low technology experience: voters self-isolate in a cab and put a preprinted sheet of paper indicating the candidate of their choice in an envelope.
After the officers check the identity of the voter, the voter casts the envelope in the ballot box and signs the list of voter names.
French electoral law codifies procedures rather strictly.
Since 1988, voting boxes have to be transparent so that voters and observers can see that no envelopes are present at the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those of voters counted and duly authorised.
