When a small group of living things (small population) is separated from the main population they came from (such as moving over a range of mountains or a river, or moving to a new island so that they cannot move back easily) they often find themselves in an environment other environment than what they had before.
This new environment has different resources and different competitors, so the new population will need different features or adaptations to be a strong competitor instead of what they needed earlier.
The original population has not changed at all, but still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, it becomes increasingly less similar to the other population.
Eventually, after thousands of years or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they will not even be able to be called the same species.
This process is called speciation, which simply means the formation of new species.
